&lt;p&gt;The ASSETS project is an initiative at The University of Tennessee at Chattanooga, UTC, designed to bridge the transition of community college transfer students into a four year engineering degree program. Transfer students face unique challenges when moving from a 2 year degree program into a 4 year degree program, including transfer shock, poor curricular alignment between the 2 year and 4 year curriculum, financial hardship, and career awareness about engineering pathways. The overall mission was to promote community among the transfer students and enhance their ability to be successful in completing their engineering degrees within a two year time frame. Project goals included four main objectives: 1) improve retention and reduce time to graduation among engineering transfer students; 2) create a Transfer Learning Community (TLC) that provides scholarships and academic support through mentoring and career development activities; 3) investigate how program activities affect academic performance, retention and graduation; and 4) establish a model for supporting engineering transfer students. The ASSETS project employed evidence-based practices to support 3 academic cohorts of transfer students by establishing a cohort-based Transfer Learning Community (TLC) course where the engaged in formal faculty &lt;br /&gt;mentoring, peer mentoring, boot camps, and career development focused activities. Students received scholarships to support their focus on academics.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A total of 37 transfer students were supported with scholarships, across the four academic years of the project. As a result of this project, 80% of the students were retained, which is a much higher retention rate than the average for transfer students. At graduation, 85% had obtained employment. The overwhelming majority of the students (90%) reported strong satisfaction with their degree program. At the program conclusion, more than half (55%) graduated from the program early or on time (within two years). These time-to-degree outcomes are better than that of the average for transfer students in engineering; the 4 year graduation rate for all Engineering students at UTC is about 35%. Ninety-one students completed the program within 3 years. The TLC course was institutionalized, and made available to all incoming transfer students in the engineering program. The most effective activities as reported by students were the financial support and the connections made through faculty and peer mentoring.&lt;/p&gt;

